The Market Dynamics of Exchange Listings

Andrew Dyer

Nov 15, 2024 ⋅  8 min read

Key Insights

  • Listing-to-date performance for futures products has been universally poor for most of 2024.
  • Initial listing rallies are usually front-run on decentralized exchanges. Trading going live usually marks a local top for an asset, with a median performance of -10-20% in the first month.
  • Funding rates are usually highly negative in the first ten days of trading; listings with the highest funding rates and open interest increase in the first five days of trading tended to perform better.
  • Listings completely change the return distribution of an asset. Assets’ daily returns, volatilities, skewness, and kurtosis all fall significantly post-listing. Listings increase pricing efficiency and decrease the occurrence of extreme outcomes, particularly outsized right-tailed moves.
  • Centralized exchanges have been going out on the risk curve with new listings, leading to larger opening rallies. They may compete more aggressively in a new regulatory environment, which could change sentiment around new CEX listings.

In 2024, the median Binance and Bybit futures listings had -9% and -22% listing-to-date returns respectively. Complaints about high listing valuations, large listing fees for projects, and souring sentiment about VC-funded protocol launches have put centralized exchanges (CEXs) under fire. While in the early stages of crypto markets CEXs were the undisputed gatekeepers of token listings, the landscape has changed. With the rise of DEXs like Hyperliquid and Raydium, apps like Moonshot and Pump.fun, and the general improvement of onchain trading UX, it’s no surprise that DEX share of spot volumes has risen to almost 14%. Why the fall from grace, and are there any inklings of a comeback for centralized exchanges?

In this report, we explain typical price patterns and investor behavior around listings, as well as touch on recent changes in CEX listing tactics.

Exchange Jargon

First, a quick primer on centralized exchange products:

  • CEXs like Binance and Bybit offer spot, futures, and options products.
  • Spot trading involves simple swaps from base assets like USDT, BTC, BNB into a desired token; users own the underlying asset they swap into at no risk of liquidation if not purchased on margin.
  • Futures can be contracts with fixed expiration dates, but most volume is done on perpetual swaps (which have no expiration) against a stablecoin base asset like USDT.
  • Perpetual swaps and their underlying spot asset can diverge in price, sometimes by a significant differential. If traders want to heavily bet in one direction with leverage and there are not many venues for doing so, differentials between the two markets may remain high until arbitrageurs step in.
  • Typical futures contracts ultimately converge to the spot price at expiry; since perpetuals have no expiry, they “enforce” convergence of prices in the two markets through the funding rate.
  • Funding is the percentage fee paid by longs to shorts (if the funding rate is positive) or shorts to longs (if the rate is negative); the rate will increase in magnitude the more the perpetual price diverges from the underlying spot price, which encourages convergence over time.
  • Funding fees are typically paid out every eight hours, although this may be shortened if the exchange finds that rates are too volatile and prices are not efficient; the baseline funding rate is usually .01% per eight hours, which translates to about 10% APR that longs must pay shorts in order to stay long.
  • Open interest (OI) represents the total number of active positions in a specific contract (both long and short); OI will increase as new positions are opened and decrease as old positions are closed.

With that out of the way, let’s discuss patterns in the data.

Listing Pumps are Still Real

Out of 105 assets that received Binance Futures listings in 2024, the average opening return in the first 12 hours of trade was around 77%. Given this is skewed by outliers to the upside, the median opening return of 12.5% is perhaps more representative. The maximum opening return was almost 3,000% for NEIROETH, and the minimum opening return was around -40% for POWR. Large exchange listings certainly still drive attention and flows in the short-term, but the price action that usually unfolds over longer periods of time has been less bullish.

First Month Action

Binance perp listings have typically declined by around 12% in the first 30 days of trade, while Bybit listings have declined ~21%.

Why are average opening returns so high if listings represent local tops in prices? Our opening returns are calculated from prices onchain or elsewhere about a day before listing, up until the first 12 hours of trading. Prices may move significantly on DEXs in anticipation of a listing, as Binance and Bybit typically announce new listing hours or days ahead of time. Most of the positive price action may occur pre-listing or during the first few hours of trade.

Across more than 100 listings over more than a year, we can see that price, funding rates, and OI follow a standard pattern when looking at median numbers. OI ramps aggressively in the first five days as traders put on new positions (both long and short). OI typically flattens around days 5 to 10 post-listing.

Funding rates are somewhat surprisingly very negative in the first days after listing, before normalizing around baseline funding. This phenomenon may happen for a few reasons:

  • Prices may have moved up significantly pre-listing, so perp traders are betting directionally against the token hoping for some mean-reversion;
  • Investors with tokens that have not vested yet may be hedging their positions upon launch;
  • Futures listings often come with or shortly after spot listings of newly launched tokens which may have unlocks in the near future; traders may be shorting ahead of future supply pressure.

For Binance futures, we attempted to discern if patterns in funding and OI were correlated with future price moves. We took the average funding rate in the first five days of each listing and then bucketed those listings into quartiles.

  • Quartile four, which represented the listings with the highest funding rates over the first five days, actually performed much better than the rest of the dataset; the effect was consistent as we moved to the other quartiles - i.e. lower starting funding rates led to worse performance in the first month.
  • We saw a similar effect when bucketing the listings by normalized OI in the first five days.
  • Higher funding rates right on listing indicates that there are more participants who want to go long the token with leverage, which certainly indicates more demand than if participants are using futures to hedge unvested allocations.

Funding and the initial OI ramp could be used as proxies for general demand or a gauge of participation that can be predictive of future prices.

Higher Efficiency = Less Volatility & Less Asymmetry

While futures listings certainly bring enhanced liquidity and price discovery, they also drastically change the risk-return profile of the average token. Daily returns and volatility are both squashed for the average token post-listing. While we do see those large opening moves in many cases, the price action afterwards changes significantly from DEX-only trading.

Not only do returns and volatility change, but the entire distribution changes shape. Skewness measures the asymmetry of the distribution on returns around its mean; positive skew indicates that there are generally more frequent small losses and fewer but larger gains. Stocks are typically negatively skewed (around -0.4), so tokens have drastically different return distributions. Returns post-listing become much less positively skewed, meaning there are much fewer right-tailed outcomes (i.e. fewer multi standard deviation up days).

Kurtosis measures the “tailedness” of a distribution, or how likely extreme outcomes are. A normal distribution with thin tails has a kurtosis of 3. Stocks are typically a bit leptokurtic, which means they have a kurtosis higher than 3 and are more prone to extreme events (both positive and negative). Token daily return distributions transition from wildly extreme to still extreme (compared to stocks) but certainly less so. Futures listings change the expected outcomes for a given token entirely.

Turning Tides

Listing performance may have been lackluster this year, but exchanges have taken note of the souring sentiment around high FDV launches and listing fees.

Binance surprised everyone on November 11th when they gave spot and futures listings to two smaller-cap memecoins. PNUT and ACT were trading around $100 million and $20 million respectively; post-listing they now sit around $2 billion and $600 million respectively. ACT was a surprising choice in particular, as it had been abandoned by its developer and was arguably fading into irrelevance. But Binance is certainly making a statement about being willing to list assets further out on the risk curve, to the benefit of die-hard holders of obscure assets. Bybit quickly listed these two assets afterwards, as the exchanges try to match offerings in high-volume listings.

Given the coming change in the regulatory environment, both Robinhood and Coinbase decided to list PEPE on November 13th. Highly sought-after spot listings can still cause large %50+ rallies like PEPE had on Wednesday. As we mentioned in our post-election coverage, if centralized exchanges are less worried about getting sued by the SEC with a new administration, it is likely we get a listing arms-race of sorts, as exchanges compete for trading volumes in the top-traded memes (or other assets). Sentiment around launches is poised to shift if this trend continues, which may reflexively lead to better post-listing performance.
